fields.name: Murray Journeay

fields.profile:
For many years, I have been studying historical seismology with a particular interest in calendar date and time differences between  effected countries during different eras.  

For most people seriously interested in earthquakes, this information is usually not so important.  Since I use planetary positions to determine likely times of seismic events of significance (6.8 magnitude or larger), it is essential that I get it as close to the actual time of occurrence as possible.

Since about 2010, I have been determining which planetary groupings parallel earthquake activity (using statistical methods).  

Much of this was inspired by RCA engineer John Nelson who's job in the '40s and '50s was to predict periods of shortwave radio interference based on similar planetary relationships.

Although I have had promising results in determining beforehand the timing of significant events (which improves as the minimum magnitude of events increases above the 6.8 magnitude baseline), knowing where they are going to pop up is much more difficult.

The Openquake project will allow me to be more knowledgeable in regards to the most likely areas of future activity.  Well, that and eclipses of the sun and if the main event is one of the 40% of earthquakes preceded by foreshock activity.

At present, I am interested in the seismic risk in the Caribbean and PNG and areas east of there. I am also interested in recent earthquakes of 7-7.1 in the South East Pacific Rise (on 9 Oct 2014) and the Northern mid-Atlantic Ridge (on 13 Feb 2015) and how those rare quakes may play into the future unfolding of larger worldwide seismic events.
